The paper deals with the Traveling Salesperson Problem with Neighborhoods (TSPN) in Euclidean space, which is a problem in computational geometry. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves the development of a Polynomial Time Approximation Scheme (PTAS), which is a technique used in approximation algorithms, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) another likely sub-category. The paper also involves the analysis of the approximation scheme, which involves the use of LP formulations and sparsification techniques, making cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity) likely sub-categories. Finally, the paper involves the study of the approximability of the problem, which involves the use of approximation algorithms and hardness results, making cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) a possible sub-category as well.
